# Minimum necessary tweaks

Everything else is either placebo, negligible gain on modern hardware, or targets edge cases. These are the ones with either (a) documented measurable impact or (b) actual bloat you're running for no reason.

## Services to disable (measurable idle reduction)

Only the ones that actually run at idle and consume resources. Use:
```powershell
Set-Service -Name <name> -StartupType Disabled
Stop-Service -Name <name> -Force
```

| Service | Why |
|---|---|
| `DiagTrack` | Connected User Experiences and Telemetry. Runs constantly, uploads data, zero benefit to you |
| `dmwappushservice` | WAP push routing, companion to DiagTrack |
| `DoSvc` | Delivery Optimization. Uses bandwidth to seed updates to other PCs |
| `MapsBroker` | Downloads map data in background even if you never use Maps |
| `WSearch` | Windows Search indexer. **Only disable if you don't use Start menu file search.** Indexing is actual disk churn |
| `SysMain` | Superfetch/Prefetch. On SSDs it's pointless writes; on HDDs keep it |
| `WerSvc` | Keep running for local crash dumps, but covered above in GPO (disable upload, keep service) |
| `RetailDemo` | Demo mode for retail displays. Useless on any real machine |
| `WbioSrvc` | Windows Biometric. Disable if no fingerprint reader/Windows Hello |
| `Fax` | Fax service. Just no |
| `TabletInputService` | Only if no touch/pen |
| `WalletService` | Microsoft Wallet. Not used by anything |
| `lfsvc` | Geolocation — already covered in GPO |
| `PcaSvc` | Program Compatibility Assistant. Scans every exe you launch |

Verify impact at idle:
```powershell
Get-Process | Where-Object { $_.CPU -gt 0 } | Sort-Object CPU -Descending | Select-Object -First 20
```

## Registry tweaks — only the ones with evidence

### 1. NetworkThrottlingIndex — **proven** DPC latency reduction

Community testing on Blur Busters showed NDIS DPC latency drop from 97µs to 32µs, and interrupt-to-process latency from 211µs to ~50µs just from this one change.

```
HKLM\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Windows NT\CurrentVersion\Multimedia\SystemProfile
NetworkThrottlingIndex = 0xFFFFFFFF
```

Not placebo — measurable in LatencyMon.

### 2. SystemResponsiveness — **proven** to reclaim reserved CPU

Windows reserves 20% of CPU for background by default. Setting to 10 gives your foreground apps that back.

```
HKLM\SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Windows NT\CurrentVersion\Multimedia\SystemProfile
SystemResponsiveness = 10
```

### 3. Win32PrioritySeparation — **measurable on some workloads, placebo on others**

Research by the apex-optimizer project and reset era testing found that **0x26 showed no statistical difference in benchmarks**, but **0x2A (short, fixed, high foreground boost)** showed real 1% low improvements on tested systems (verified on 7800X3D and 9800X3D with CapFrameX).

```
HKLM\SYSTEM\CurrentControlSet\Control\PriorityControl
Win32PrioritySeparation = 0x2A (hex) / 42 (decimal)
```

If your machine is shared work+play or you multitask heavily, use 0x29 (medium boost) instead — safer on mixed workloads.

### 4. Memory compression off — **measurable** CPU savings on 16GB+ systems

```powershell
Disable-MMAgent -MemoryCompression
```

Compression costs CPU cycles. On systems with plenty of RAM, it's pure overhead. **Keep it on if you have ≤8GB** — then it's earning its keep.

### 5. Core parking off — **measurable** response-time improvement

Default plans park cores and take 1-10ms to unpark them when work arrives. That delay shows up as UI hitches.

```powershell
# Activate Ultimate Performance (already unparks everything)
powercfg -duplicatescheme e9a42b02-d5df-448d-aa00-03f14749eb61
powercfg /setactive e9a42b02-d5df-448d-aa00-03f14749eb61
```

Or on your existing plan, unhide and set min cores to 100%:
```powershell
powercfg -attributes SUB_PROCESSOR 0cc5b647-c1df-4637-891a-dec35c318583 -ATTRIB_HIDE
# Then powercfg.cpl -> advanced -> Processor -> Core parking min cores = 100%
```

### 6. HAGS on — **measurable** DWM latency improvement on supported GPUs

```
HKLM\SYSTEM\CurrentControlSet\Control\GraphicsDrivers
HwSchMode = 2
```

Reboot required. Requires RTX 2000+/RX 5000+.

## What I am NOT including and why

- **Win32PrioritySeparation = 0x26** — apex-optimizer benchmarks showed no statistical difference vs default
- **Timer resolution via bcdedit** — causes more problems than it solves on modern systems; Windows 11 22H2 changed how this works. Apps that need 1ms already request it dynamically
- **Large TCP tweaks** (RSS queues, offloads) — drivers manage this correctly now
- **Nagle disable / TcpAckFrequency** — only matters for competitive gaming or low-latency finance; default is correct for 99% of use
- **DisablePagingExecutive** — no measurable benefit unless you're CPU-starved AND have huge RAM; even then marginal
- **Service pruning beyond the above list** — per Windows Forum analysis, services are on-demand activated in Windows 10/11 and consume zero resources when idle. Disabling 30 services you don't use saves almost nothing vs disabling the 5 that actually run
- **Visual effects off** — helps on very old hardware; on anything from the last 5 years the GPU handles this for free

## Order to apply

1. Disable the services list — biggest idle reduction
2. `powercfg` to Ultimate Performance — biggest "feels faster" win
3. NetworkThrottlingIndex + SystemResponsiveness in one reg write — biggest latency win
4. Win32PrioritySeparation = 0x2A — try it, test for a day, revert if something feels off
5. HAGS on if supported GPU
6. MemoryCompression off if 16GB+

Reboot after step 3, verify with:
```powershell
Get-Process | Measure-Object | Select-Object Count    # process count at idle
Get-NetTCPConnection -State Established | Measure-Object | Select-Object Count
```

You should see a noticeable drop in both.

That's it. Every other "tweak" you'll find on the internet is either covered by these, already fixed in modern Windows defaults, or placebo.
